					<marginalia_text>
						vnum pluribus: sed vnum in sua classe excellentem, 
						et absolutu[m].
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Eaq[ue] vnica ratione,
						tam mirificè pra[e]ter ca[e]teros
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						profecit Ferdinandus Corduba, in expedita, solidaq[ue]
						cognitione tot, antarumq[ue] artium. Plurimi multitudine artificu[m],
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Gonzalo Fernández de Córdoba"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						parum didicerunt:
						ille paucitate artificum effecit,
						vt nihil
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						ferè ignoraret: vnius artis perfectionem vni debens
						perfectissimo artifici: et tot habens artes, quot
						Artifices.
						Sed ad ungue[m]
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						( singula; et cum auctoritate.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				One great authority is enough for anything, especially when he is not idling about with many things. The examen of intellects completely prefers one over many: but one excellent and complete in its class. 
				And for that one same reason, Gonzalo Fernández de Córdoba accomplished so many things of the pillars of art so amazingly beyond other men in unencumbered and solid knowledge. 
				Many have learned little from a multitude of artists: that man found success with a scarcity of artists, as he hardly ever ignored anything, owing the perfection of one art to one most perfect
				artist: and having as many arts, as  artists. But the singular ones by heart, and with authority. 
		 </translation>
		</marginalia>
		
